1. What is an iFrame?
- iFrame (Inline Frame) is an HTML element used to embed another webpage inside the current webpage.
- Simple Definition:
    - iFrame is like a "window" , inside a webpage that shows another webpage

2. Why iFrames are used?
- To embded:
    - Youtube videos
    - Google maps
    - Ads
    - External websites
    - Payment gateways

3. Basic Structure of iFrame
    <iframe>
    src="page.html"
    height = "400"
    width = "600"
    </iframe>

4. Important Attributes of iFrame
Attribute & Meaning
-------------------
- src -> URL of the page to embed
- height -> Height of frame
- width -> Width of frame
- name -> Used for switching frames
- frameborder -> Adds/Removes border (deprecated)
- allow -> Permission (camera , mic etc)

5. Types of iFrames (Important for Interviews)
- Static iFrame
    - Fixed content
    - Does not change dynamically
- Dynamic iFrame
    - Loaded using Javascript/AJAX
    - Changes without page reload

6. iFrame Handling in Selenium (VERY IMPORTANT)
- Selenium cannot directly access elements inside iFrame
- We must switch switch to alert

    - 3 Ways to Switch iFrame in Selenium (Python)
    1. By Index
        driver.switch_to_frame(0)
    2. By Name or ID
        driver.switch_to_frame("frameName")
    3. By WebElement
        frame=driver.find_element(By.TAG_NAME , "iframe")
        driver.switch_to_frame(frame)
    
🔙 Switch Back to Main Page
- driver.switch_to.default_content()

🔙 Switch to Parent Frame
- driver.switch_to.parent_frame()

7. iFrame Handling Flow (Real Selenium Logic)
Open Website
   ↓
Find iFrame
   ↓
Switch to iFrame
   ↓
Perform Actions
   ↓
Switch back to default page


8. Common Problems with iFrames in Selenium
- ElementNotFound
- NoSuchElementException
- StaleElementReferenceException

- Reason
    - Because you trying to access elements without switching to frame

9. How to Identify iFrame in DOM
- Using DevTools:
    <iframe id= "login-frame"></iframe>
- XPath:
    //iframe

10. Advanced Concepts
- Nested iFrames (Frame inside Frame)
    Main Page
    ↓
    iFrame 1
    ↓
    iFrame 2

- Selenium Handling:
    driver.switch_to.frame("frame1")
    driver.switch_to.frame("frame2")

- To go back:
    driver.switch_to.default_content()

- Hidden iFrames
    - Not Visibl on UI
    - Loaded in background
    - Still accessible via selenium

- Cross-Domain iFrames
    - Loaded from different domain
    - Security restriction applies (SOP - same origin policy)

